<section xml:id="list-algorithms-iterators_using-iterators"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Using Iterators</title>

  <p>
    Again, one of the chief benefits of using iterators is that they provide a uniform interface for safely working with different types of collections. Once we have build an iterator for our linked list, we can use any of the standard algorithms that work with iterators. This program has some examples of doing so:
  </p>
  
  <listing>
    <program label="list-algorithms-iterators_using-iterators-program-1"
       interactive="activecode" add-files="list-algorithms-iterators_using-iterators-program-1-helpers"
       highlight-lines="23,29,33">
<xi:include href="../../programs/list-algorithms-iterators/using-iterators-1.cpp" parse="text"/>
    </program>
  </listing>

  <p>Below is the listing for the updated <pf>SinglyLinkedList</pf> class with iterator support that this program depends on. Lines relating to the iterator implementation are highlighted, the rest of the code should already be familiar from the previous chapter.</p>
  
